\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kernel density estimation with fixed bandwidth has become the most common
 method to estimate unknown densities of continuous random variables.
 The standard kernel density estimator (KDE) is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{f}_{h}\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{nh}\sum_{i=1}^{n}K\left(\frac{X_{i}-x}{h}\right),\label{eq:standard-kde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 i.i.d.
 samples of a univariate random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 drawn from a generating distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a kernel that integrates to unity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the bandwidth which controls the smoothness of the estimator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Silverman1986"

\end_inset

.
 We call a kernel 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 if it is invariant with respect to exchange of the sample it represents
 and the evaluation point, i.e.
 the point at which it is evaluated.
 Typical kernels such as the Gaussian or Epanechnikov kernel are even functions
 such that the contributions in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:standard-kde"

\end_inset

 are indeed symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is only supported on a (semi-)bounded interval, standard KDEs suffer from
 boundary bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Silverman1986"

\end_inset

.
 Brown and Chen observed that the boundary problem can be resolved by choosing
 a kernel that has the same support as the generating density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Brown1999, Chen2000a"

\end_inset

.
 They pioneered the use of asymmetric kernels, i.e.
 kernels that are not invariant under exchange of the evaluation point and
 the associated sample, and developed an estimator based on beta distributions
 for densities with bounded support.
 Chen used gamma distributions to develop an estimator for densities supported
 on the positive real line 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chen2000"

\end_inset

 which spurred further research into density estimation for positive random
 variables using asymmetric kernels: log-normal and Birnbaum-Saunders kernels
 reduce the bias near the boundary 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jin2003"

\end_inset

.
 Scaillet employed inverse Gaussian and reciprocal inverse Gaussian kernels
 to eliminate the dependence of the bias on the first derivative of the
 generating distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Scaillet2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two different approaches to constructing density estimators from
 asymmetric kernels which are identical if the kernels are symmetric: Let
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(t;\mu,\sigma)$
\end_inset

 be the probability distribution of a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 which has most of its mass in the vicinity of 
\begin_inset Formula $t\approx\mu$
\end_inset

 and becomes more sharply peaked as the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 The distribution is normalised such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{a}^{b}dt\,W(t;\mu,\sigma)=1\label{eq:asymmetric-normalisation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 For the remainder of the manuscript, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 will refer to the lower and upper bound of the interval on which both the
 kernel and the generating distribution are supported.
 The majority of asymmetric kernel density estimators are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{f}_{h}(x)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=0}^{n}W(X_{i};x,h).
\]

\end_inset

We call such estimators 
\emph on
irregular
\emph default
 estimators because the evaluation point is treated as a parameter of the
 distribution and the sample is treated as a parameter.
 They have been criticised because they are not valid densities themselves,
 i.e.
 they do not integrate to unity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuruwita2010"

\end_inset

.
 Jeoan and Kim obtained an estimator that is a valid density by treating
 the evaluation point as a random variable and parametrising the gamma distribut
ion with the associated sample 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jeon2014"

\end_inset

.
 More generally, we can define a 
\emph on
regular
\emph default
 estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{f}_{h}(x)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=0}^{n}W(x;X_{i},h)
\]

\end_inset

which is guaranteed to be a properly normalised distribution by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:asymmetric-normalisation"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The performance of density estimators is usually judged by their asymptotic
 mean (integrated) square error in the limit of a large number of samples
 and small bandwidth.
 Intuitively, even asymmetric kernels become sharply peaked in this limit
 and we can approximate them by symmetric kernels.
 In Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:balloon"

\end_inset

, we show that Chen's irregular estimator with gamma kernels is asymptotically
 equivalent to a 
\emph on
balloon
\emph default
 estimator, i.e.
 a symmetric KDE whose bandwidth depends on the evaluation point.
 In Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:sample-point"

\end_inset

, we show that Jeon's regular estimator with gamma kernels is asymptotically
 equivalent to a 
\emph on
sample-point
\emph default
 estimator, i.e.
 a symmetric KDE whose bandwidth depends on the samples.
 We derive the bias, variance and mean (integrated) square error of generic
 balloon and sample-point estimators in the respective section.
 We apply the results to log-normal, Birnbaum-Saunders, inverse Gaussian,
 and reciprocal inverse Gaussian kernels in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:application"

\end_inset

 and develop plugin methods for bandwidth selection.
 In Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:discussion"

\end_inset

, we discuss our results, provide advice on which estimator to use under
 a variety of circumstances and outline future work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extended balloon estimators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:balloon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate densities supported on the positive real line, Chen proposed
 the irregular estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{f}_{\sigma}(x) & =\sum_{i=0}^{n}\underbrace{\gammakernel\left(X_{i};\frac{x}{\sigma^{2}}+1,\sigma^{2}\right)}_{W(X_{i};x,\sigma)},\label{eq:permuted-gamma-estimator}\\
\text{where}\quad\gammakernel(t;k,\theta) & =\frac{t^{k-1}}{\Gamma(k)\theta^{k}}\exp\left(-\frac{t}{\theta}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

is the distribution of a gamma random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 with shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For large shape parameters, the gamma distribution is well-approximated
 by a normal distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $k\theta$
\end_inset

 and bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\sqrt{k}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Johnson1994"

\end_inset

.
 Chen parametrised the gamma kernel such that its mode is equal to the associate
d sample.
 Because the kernel is right-skewed, its mean differs by a small shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The effective bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=\sigma\sqrt{x+\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

 depends on the evaluation point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we build on the results by Terrell and Scott to derive
 the asymptotic properties of estimators with symmetric kernels whose mean
 differs from the associated sample and whose bandwidth depends on the evaluatio
n point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An order-
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 kernel is a univariate probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}m_{k}\left(\alpha,\beta\right) & \equiv\int_{\alpha}^{\beta}dz\,K(z)z^{k} & \kappa\left(\alpha,\beta\right) & \equiv\int_{\alpha}^{\beta}dz\,K^{2}(z)\\
m_{k} & \equiv\lim_{-\alpha,\beta\rightarrow\infty}m_{k}\left(\alpha,\beta\right) & \kappa & \equiv\lim_{-\alpha,\beta\rightarrow\infty}\kappa\left(\alpha,\beta\right)\\
m_{k} & =1\quad\text{if }k=0,\,p & m_{k} & =0\quad\text{if }0<k<p,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:kernel-properties}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 moment of the kernel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a unit-variance Gaussian with zero mean is a second-order kernel.
 For a Gaussian kernel and sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $-\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the quantity 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cite the moment expression.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
m_{k}(\alpha,\beta)=\frac{2^{k/2-1}}{\sqrt{\pi}}\Gamma\left(\frac{k+1}{2}\right)\left(1+(-1)^{k}\right)+\frac{\alpha^{k-1}\exp\left(-\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\\
-\frac{\beta^{k-1}\exp\left(-\frac{\beta^{2}}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{2\pi}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\alpha^{k-2}\exp\left(-\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2}\right)-\beta^{k-2}\exp\left(-\frac{\beta^{2}}{2}\right)\right)
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

approaches its limiting value exponentially quickly.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa(\alpha,\beta)=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{\pi}}+\frac{\exp\left(-\alpha^{2}\right)}{4\pi\alpha}-\frac{\exp\left(-\beta^{2}\right)}{4\pi\beta}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\exp\left(-\alpha^{2}\right)}{\alpha^{2}}-\frac{\exp\left(-\beta^{2}\right)}{\beta^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having formalised the notion of a kernel, we extend the expression for balloon
 estimators by adding a small shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 to the argument of the kernel and derive their mean square error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An extended balloon estimator is a kernel density estimator whose bandwidth
 depends on the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at which it is evaluated, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{f}_{h}(x)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{h(x)}K\left(\frac{X_{i}-x-\delta(x)}{h(x)}\right),\label{eq:balloon-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 is a shift which vanishes in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example for the shift?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean square error (MSE) of a density estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}_{h}(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mse_{h}(x)=\left\langle \left(f(x)-\hat{f}_{h}(x)\right)^{2}\right\rangle ,
\]

\end_inset

where the expectation is taken with respect to the generating density 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We rewrite the MSE in terms of squared bias and variance such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mse_{h}(x) & =\bias_{h}^{2}(x)+\var_{h}(x),\\
\text{where}\quad\bias_{h}(x) & =\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle -f(x)\\
\text{and}\quad\var_{h}(x) & =\frac{1}{n}\left(\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle -\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle ^{2}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To make further progress, we need to evaluate the first two moments of the
 estimator in the limit of small bandwidth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:balloon-moments"

\end_inset

 The first and second moments of an extended balloon estimator are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & =\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}A_{k}m_{k}(z(a,x),z(b,x))\label{eq:balloon-first-moment}\\
\text{and}\quad\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & =\frac{f(x)\kappa(z(a,x),z(b,x))}{h(x)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{0}(x)\right),\label{eq:balloon-second-moment}\\
\text{where}\quad A_{k} & =h^{k}(x)\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(j)}(x)}{k!(j-k)!}\delta^{j-k}(x),\label{eq:balloon-first-moment-coefficient}\\
z(y,x) & =\frac{y-x-\delta(x)}{h(x)},\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

and the factorial is defined such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0!\equiv1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j!\equiv0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $j<0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What happens if 
\begin_inset Formula $k>j$
\end_inset

? Do we need to impose constraints on the relative speed at which the two
 quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 vanish?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See the appendix for a proof.
 Consider the behaviour of the density estimator at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that is several bandwidths larger (smaller) than the lower (upper) boundary
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(x,a)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $z(x,b)$
\end_inset

) is a large negative (positive) number.
 We can approximate the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}(z(a,x),z(b,x))$
\end_inset

 by its limiting value 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}$
\end_inset

 under these conditions, and only the 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=p$
\end_inset

 terms contribute to leading order in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:balloon-first-moment"

\end_inset

.
 The intermediate terms vanish because 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<p$
\end_inset

 according to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:kernel-properties"

\end_inset

 and terms with 
\begin_inset Formula $k>p$
\end_inset

 have a higher order dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 according to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:balloon-first-moment-coefficient"

\end_inset

.
 We can make corresponding arguments for 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting into the expression for the first two moments in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:balloon-first-moment"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:balloon-second-moment"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & \approx{\color{red}A_{0}}+{\color{blue}A_{p}}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{p+1}\left(x\right)\right)\\
 & ={\color{red}f(x)+\delta(x)f'(x)}+{\color{blue}\frac{h^{p}(x)}{p!}f^{(p)}(x)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{p+1}\left(x\right)+\delta^{2}\left(x\right)\right)\\
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & \approx\frac{\kappa f(x)}{h(x)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{0}(x)\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

To leading order in 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

, the MSE is 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why is the bias extended to first order and the variance only to zero order?
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mse_{h}(x)=\left[\delta(x)f'(x)+\frac{h^{p}(x)}{p!}f^{(p)}(x)\right]^{2}+\frac{\kappa f(x)}{nh(x)}
\]

\end_inset

which is the same as the expression derived by Terrell and Scott if we let
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Any dependence of the bias on the first derivative of the generating distributi
on is due to the shift between the kernel mean and the associated sample
 as Chen noted in the context of irregular gamma estimators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chen2000"

\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
TAH: Can we provide a continuity argument why the results still hold near
 the boundary?
\series default
 The mean integrated square error is a global quality measure and is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mise_{h}=\int_{a}^{b}dx\left[\delta(x)f'(x)+\frac{h^{p}(x)}{p!}f^{(p)}(x)\right]^{2}+\frac{\kappa}{n}\left\langle h^{-1}(x)\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We noted that the kernels of the irregular estimator in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:permuted-gamma-estimator"

\end_inset

 converge to a Gaussian kernel with shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 and variable bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)=\sigma\sqrt{x+\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

 such that its MSE and MISE are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mse_{\sigma}(x) & =\sigma^{4}\left[f'(x)+\frac{xf''}{2}\right]^{2}+\frac{f(x)}{2n\sigma\sqrt{\pi x}}\\
\mise_{\sigma} & =\sigma^{4}\int_{0}^{\infty}dx\left[f'(x)+\frac{xf''}{2}\right]^{2}+\frac{\left\langle x^{-1/2}\right\rangle }{2n\sigma\sqrt{\pi}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which agree with the expressions derived by Chen after reparametrisation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chen2000"

\end_inset

.
 The MISE can be optimised by cross validation or by using a reference distribut
ion which enables us to obtain a plugin method for estimating the bandwidth.
 The parametric form of the reference distribution is largely a free choice;
 we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is approximately log-normal with logarithmic mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and logarithmic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 for convenience.
 Substituting yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mise_{\sigma}=\sigma^{4}\frac{\exp\left(-3\mu+\frac{9\Sigma^{2}}{4}\right)\left(12+20\Sigma^{2}+9\Sigma^{4}\right)}{128\sqrt{\pi}\Sigma^{4}}+\frac{\exp\left(-\frac{\mu}{2}+\frac{\Sigma^{2}}{8}\right)}{2n\sigma\sqrt{\pi}}
\]

\end_inset

and setting the derivative of the MISE with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to zero yields the optimal scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{*}=\frac{2^{4/5}\Sigma\exp\left(\frac{\mu}{2}-\frac{17\Sigma^{2}}{40}\right)}{\left(12+20\Sigma^{2}+9\Sigma^{4}\right)^{1/5}}n^{-1/5}.
\]

\end_inset

The expression allows us to obtain a bandwidth by estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 from the data without the need for computationally-expensive cross-validation.
 Plugin bandwidth estimators are particularly useful for preliminary data
 exploration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Extended sample-point estimators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:sample-point"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
irregular estimators have been criticised because they are not properly
 normalised densities themselves.
 Jeoan and Kim 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jeon2014"

\end_inset

 exchanged the evaluation point and samples in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:permuted-gamma-estimator"

\end_inset

 and obtained the regular estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{f}_{\sigma}(x)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\underbrace{\gammakernel\left(x;\frac{X_{i}}{\sigma^{2}}+1,\sigma^{2}\right)}_{W(x;X_{i},\sigma)}.\label{eq:regular-gamma-estimator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the limit of a small 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 summand converges to a Gaussian with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}+\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 and bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X_{i})=\sigma\sqrt{X_{i}+\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

 which depends on the corresponding sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the remainder of this section, we derive the asymptotic properties of
 estimators with kernels whose mean differs from the associated sample by
 a small amount and whose bandwidth is sample-dependent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An extended sample-point estimator is a kernel density estimator whose bandwidth
 depends on the samples 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{f}_{h}(x)=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{h(X_{i})}K\left(\frac{X_{i}+\delta(X_{i})-x}{h(X_{i})}\right),\label{eq:sample-point-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(X_{i})$
\end_inset

 is a shift which vanishes in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X_{i})\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the previous section, we evaluate the first two moments assuming the
 bandwidth is small.
 See the appendix for a proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:sample-point-moments"

\end_inset

 Provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(y,x)=\frac{y+\delta(y)-x}{h(y)}$
\end_inset

 is a monotonically increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, the first and second moments of an extended sample-point estimator are
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & =\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}B_{k}m_{k}(z(a,x),z(b,x))\\
\text{and}\quad\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & =\frac{f(x)\kappa(z(a,x),z(b,x))}{h(x)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{0}(x)\right),\\
\text{where}\quad B_{k} & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{k!(j-k)!}\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial x^{j}}\left(f(x)h^{k}(x)(-\delta(x))^{j-k}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the same arguments as in the previous section, the first two moments
 are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & \approx{\color{red}B_{0}}+{\color{blue}B_{p}}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{p+1}(x)\right)\nonumber \\
 & ={\color{red}f(x)-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\delta\left(x\right)f'\left(x\right)\right)}+{\color{blue}\frac{1}{p!}\frac{\partial^{p}}{\partial x^{p}}\left(h^{p}\left(x\right)f\left(x\right)\right)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{p+1}(x)+\delta^{2}(x)\right)\label{eq:regular-first-moment}\\
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & \approx\frac{\kappa f(x)}{h(x)}+\mathcal{O}\left(h^{0}(x)\right).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why is there a 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{0}$
\end_inset

 term?
\end_layout

\end_inset

The MSE and MISE are thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mse_{h}(x) & =\left[-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\delta(x)f(x)\right)+\frac{1}{p!}\frac{\partial^{p}}{\partial x^{p}}\left(h^{p}(x)f(x)\right)\right]^{2}+\frac{\kappa f(x)}{nh(x)}\label{eq:regular-mse}\\
\mise_{h} & =\int_{a}^{b}dx\left[-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\delta(x)f(x)\right)+\frac{1}{p!}\frac{\partial^{p}}{\partial x^{p}}\left(h^{p}(x)f(x)\right)\right]^{2}+\frac{\kappa}{n}\left\langle h^{-1}(x)\right\rangle .\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

to leading order in 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 which agrees with the expression derived by Terrell and Scott if we let
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Terrell1992"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jeoan and Kim were only able to obtain an upper bound for the MSE of the
 estimator defined in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:regular-gamma-estimator"

\end_inset

 but using the method developed above, we can provide an explicit form:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mse_{h}(x)=\frac{\sigma^{4}}{4}\left[xf''(x)\right]^{2}+\frac{f(x)}{2n\sigma\sqrt{\pi x}}.
\]

\end_inset

Employing the log-normal distribution as a reference distribution, and optimisin
g the MISE with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 yields the following plug-in estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{*}=\frac{2^{4/5}\Sigma\exp\left(\frac{\mu}{2}-\frac{17\Sigma^{2}}{40}\right)}{\left(12+4\Sigma^{2}+\Sigma^{4}\right)^{1/5}}n^{-1/5}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, for the Jeon and Kim choice of gamma kernel, the bias arising
 from the shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 cancels contributions involving 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 from the third term in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:regular-first-moment"

\end_inset

.
 This begs the question under which conditions the bias of extended sample-point
 estimators with second-order kernels are independent of the first derivative
 of the generating density.
 We expand the bias term in square brackets in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:regular-mse"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 and find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\bias_{h}(x)=f(x)\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(h(x)h'(x)-\delta(x)\right)\\
+f'(x)\left(2h(x)h'(x)-\delta(x)\right)+f''(x)\frac{h^{2}(x)}{2}.
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

Setting the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 to zero yields the coupled differential equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(h(x)h'(x)-\delta(x)\right) & =0\label{eq:smoothing-bias-f1}\\
2h(x)h'(x)-\delta(x) & =0.\label{eq:smoothing-bias-f2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Substituting Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-bias-f2"

\end_inset

 into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-bias-f1"

\end_inset

 and integrating gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(x)=C,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 Plugging back into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-bias-f2"

\end_inset

 we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2h(x)h'(x) & =C\\
\therefore h^{2}(x) & =Cx+D,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is another constant.
 Consequently, any extended sample-point estimator with second-order kernel
 whose bias is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 must either have an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-independent shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=C$
\end_inset

 and squared bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}(x)$
\end_inset

 that grows proportionally to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, or have no shift and constant bandwidth.
 Jeon's estimator belongs to this class but is not the only estimator with
 these property as we shall see in the next section.
\end_layout

