\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tbl:asymptotic-properties"

\end_inset

List of kernels with their asymptotic variance.
 The bias and optimal plugin smoothing scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{*}$
\end_inset

 are shown separately for perturbed and regular estimators.
 The last row shows an alternative parametrisation for the RIG kernel.
 See the main text for details.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the methods developed above to derive the asymptotic properties of
 regular and irregular estimators.
 The gamma, log-normal (LN), Birnbaum-Saunders (BS), inverse Gaussian (IG)
 and reciprocal inverse Gaussian (RIG) distributions are listed in Tbl.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tbl:kernels"

\end_inset

.
 To serve as a kernel, we parametrise the distributions in terms of the
 evaluation point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, associated sample 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, and bandwidth parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, all kernels converge to a normal distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\delta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 such that our method is applicable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Johnson1994"

\end_inset

.
 The parametrisation for regular estimators can be obtained by exchanging
 the role of the evaluation point and the associated sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic bias and variance for irregular and regular estimators are
 listed in Tbl.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tbl:asymptotic-properties"

\end_inset

.
 The expressions for the asymptotics of irregular estimators agree with
 the expressions in the original papers after reparametrisation.
 Because irregular BS and LN estimators have a higher-order dependence on
 the evaluation point than the irregular gamma estimator, they have smaller
 bias near the boundary which has been confirmed by simulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jin2003"

\end_inset

.
 The same should apply to the irregular IG estimator because its bias is
 cubic in the evaluation point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regular estimators with LN, BS, and RIG kernels are new contributions
 although the LN kernel is equivalent to a log-transform of the data followed
 by standard kernel density estimation using Gaussian kernels.
 The method we have developed is not applicable to regular estimators with
 RIG kernels because the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left(y,x\right)=\frac{y-x}{\sigma y^{3/2}}$
\end_inset

 is monotonically increasing with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 does not hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the bias of a regular estimator is independent of the first
 derivative of the generating density if its kernels (a) have mean that
 differs from the associated sample by a constant and (b) have squared bandwidth
 that grows proportionally with the associated sample.
 We reparametrise the RIG kernel to satisfy these properties.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sigma^{-2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(x\right)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=\sigma\sqrt{x+2\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting estimator shares its asymptotic propeties with the regular
 gamma estimator.
 All estimators achieve the same 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{-4/5}$
\end_inset

 convergence rate as Gaussian KDEs because their MISE is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{4}E+\left(\sigma n\right)^{-1}F$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are numbers that do not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two fundamentally different approaches to constructing density
 estimators from asymmetric kernesl because they are not invariant to exchange
 of the evaluation point and the associated sample.
 On the one hand, irregular estimators are widely used and their asymptotic
 properties are known for a range of distributions including gamma, log-normal,
 Birnbaum-Saunders, inverse Gaussian and reciprocal inverse Gaussian distributio
ns.
 They are not properly-normalised densities.
 In the limit of small bandwidths, we have developed a unified approach
 to evaluate the asymptotic properties of irregular estimators which makes
 use of the kernels converging to Gaussians whose bandwidth depends on the
 evaluation point.
 The bias of the estimator depends on the first derivative of the generating
 density if the mean of the asymptotic kernel differs from the associated
 sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regular estimators, on the other hand, are valid densities themselves but
 are not widely used.
 In the limit of small bandwidths, regular kernels are well-approximated
 by Gaussians whose bandwidth depends on the associated sample.
 Assuming that the bandwidth does not depend on the sample superlinearly,
 we derived the asymptotic properties of such estimators.
 The bias of regular estimators is independent of the first derivative of
 the generating distribution if (a) the mean of the kernel differs from
 the associated by a constant and (b) the bandwidth is proportional to the
 associated sample.
 We proposed regular estimators with log-normal, Birnbaum-Saunders and reciproca
l inverse Gaussian kernels.
 Plugin methods for bandwidth estimation are provided for both irregular
 and regular estimators using the log-normal distribution as a reference
 distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the generating density is expected to have a large gradients, the regular
 gamma estimator, the reparametrised RIG estimator proposed here, and the
 irregular IG/RIG estimators are suitable because their bias is independent
 of the first derivative.
 The irregular LN, BS, IG and RIG estimators as well as the regular gamma
 estimator and the reparametrised RIG estimator have relatively low bias
 near the boundary at the origin and are appropriate for data that is clustered
 near zero such as high frequency trading volumes.
 Estimators whose effective bandwidth has a higher-order dependence on the
 evaluation point should be used for heavily-skewed data to avoid spurious
 wiggles in the tails of the distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In future work, we would like to apply our approach to further kernels and
 conduct a simulation study of the finite-sample properties of the estimators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
\start_of_appendix
Appendix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:balloon-moments"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The first moment of the extended balloon estimator defined in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:balloon-definition"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle =\int_{a}^{b}\frac{dy}{h(x)}K\left(\frac{y-x-\delta(x)}{h(x)}\right)f(y).
\]

\end_inset

We make the change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $z(y,x)=\frac{y-x-\delta(x)}{h(x)}$
\end_inset

 and expand 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a power series about 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & =\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\,K\left(z\right)f(x+zh(x)+\delta(x))\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(j)}(x)}{j!}\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\,K\left(z\right)(zh(x)+\delta(x))^{j}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Applying the binomial theorem yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & =\sum_{j,k=0}^{\infty}\tbinom{j}{k}\frac{f^{(j)}(x)}{j!}h^{k}(x)\delta^{j-k}(x)\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\,K\left(z\right)z^{k}\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}A_{k}m_{k}(z(a,x),z(b,x))\\
\text{where}\quad A_{k} & =h^{k}(x)\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\tbinom{j}{k}\frac{f^{(j)}(x)}{j!}h^{k}(x)\delta^{j-k}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The second moment is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle =\int_{a}^{b}\frac{dy}{h^{2}(x)}K^{2}\left(\frac{y-x-\delta(x)}{h(x)}\right)f(y).
\]

\end_inset

Using the same method as above and dropping higher-order terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(j)}(x)}{j!h(x)}\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\,K^{2}\left(z\right)(zh(x)+\delta(x))^{j}\\
 & =\frac{f(x)\kappa(z(a,x),z(b,x))}{h(x)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:sample-point-moments"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The first moment of the extended sample-point estimator defined in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sample-point-definition"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle =\int_{a}^{b}\frac{dy}{h(y)}K\left(\frac{y+\delta(y)-x}{h(y)}\right)f(y).
\]

\end_inset

We make the change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $z(y,x)=\frac{y+\delta(y)-x}{h(y)}$
\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(y,x)$
\end_inset

 is monotonically increasing such that the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $y(z)$
\end_inset

 exists and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle =\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\,\frac{K\left(z\right)f(y(z))}{1+\delta'(y(z))-zh'(z(y,x))}.\label{eq:smoothing-first-moment-transformed}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, the integrand 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}(z,x)$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-first-moment-transformed"

\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}(z,x)=\frac{1}{2\pi i}\oint_{\gamma}dy\,\frac{K\left(z\right)f(y)}{y+\delta(y)-x-zh(y)},\label{eq:smoothing-first-moment-contour}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a right-hand contour around the pole defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $y+\delta(y)-x-zh(y)=0$
\end_inset

 and the point 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

.
 We expand the integrand in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-first-moment-contour"

\end_inset

 as a power series in 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)z-\delta(y)$
\end_inset

 and find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{I}(z,x)=\frac{1}{2\pi i}\oint_{\gamma}dy\,\frac{K\left(z\right)f(y)}{y-x}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left(\frac{zh(y)-\delta(y)}{y-x}\right)^{j}.
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 term in the sum gives rise to a pole of order 
\begin_inset Formula $j+1$
\end_inset

.
 After expansion using the binomial theorem, the corresponding residue is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{j}(z,x) & =\frac{1}{j!}\left[\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial y^{j}}\left(f(y)K(z)\left(zh(y)-\delta(y)\right)^{j}\right)\right]_{y=x}\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\tbinom{j}{k}\frac{K(z)z^{k}}{j!}\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial x^{j}}\left(f(x)h^{k}(x)(-\delta(x))^{j-k}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}(z,x)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}R_{j}(z,x)$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting back into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:smoothing-first-moment-transformed"

\end_inset

 and integrating term by term yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}(x)\right\rangle  & =\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}B_{k}m_{k}(z(a,x),z(b,x)),\\
\text{where}\quad B_{k} & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{\tbinom{j}{k}}{j!}\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial x^{j}}\left(f(x)h^{k}(x)(-\delta(x))^{j-k}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The second moment is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle =\int_{a}^{b}\frac{dy}{h^{2}(y)}K^{2}\left(\frac{y+\delta(y)-x}{h(y)}\right)f(y).
\]

\end_inset

Using the same method as above and dropping higher-order terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle \hat{f}_{h}^{2}(x)\right\rangle  & =\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}\frac{dz}{h(y(z))}\frac{K^{2}\left(z\right)f(y(z))}{1+\delta'(y(z))-zh'(y(z))}\\
 & =\sum_{j,k=0}^{\infty}\tbinom{j}{k}\int_{z(a,x)}^{z(b,x)}dz\frac{K(z)z^{k}}{j!}\frac{\partial^{j}}{\partial x^{j}}\left(f(x)h^{k-1}(x)(-\delta(x))^{j-k}\right)\\
 & =\frac{f(x)\kappa(z(a,x),z(b,x))}{h(x)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
bibfiles "/Users/tillhoffmann/Google Drive/papers/library"
options "unsrt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

